            <h2>Welcome to Week 3: The Breakthrough Week</h2>
            <p>You've built your foundation. You understand how your brain creates pain. You can observe sensations without immediate fear. Now we're ready for the breakthrough work: gently approaching your pelvic area with all your new skills, and proving through provocative testing that your brain generates many of your symptoms.</p>
            
            <div class="endo-reminder-box">
                <h3>🌱 Your Endo Reality Check</h3>
                <p><strong>Remember: You have endometriosis AND your nervous system is amplifying it.</strong></p>
                <p>Think of it this way: If endo is a match causing a small flame, your nervous system has turned it into a bonfire. We're not denying the match exists - we're working on controlling the bonfire. Even reducing amplification by 50% would transform your daily life.</p>
                <p style="margin-top: 10px;"><em>Other women with endo have vastly different pain levels. The difference? Neural amplification. You can dial yours down.</em></p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="week-overview">
                <h3>🎯 This Week's Breakthrough Goals</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Gentle somatic tracking of actual pelvic sensations (60 seconds at a time)</li>
                    <li>Prove your brain creates symptoms through imagination (provocative testing)</li>
                    <li>Identify which emotions instantly trigger pelvic tension</li>
                    <li>Have a conversation with your pain to understand its protective role</li>
                    <li>Begin tiny exposures to feared activities</li>
                    <li>Map your life timeline to understand when/why pain began</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="warning-box">
                <h4>⚠️ Week 3 Safety Rules</h4>
                <p><strong>1.</strong> Never force through severe pain - work only at the edges of comfort</p>
                <p><strong>2.</strong> If panic arises during pelvic tracking, immediately return to hands/feet</p>
                <p><strong>3.</strong> Success is measured by doing the exercise, NOT by being symptom-free</p>
                <p><strong>4.</strong> Setbacks are your brain testing new patterns - they're temporary and normal</p>
            </div>
