            <!-- Day 17 -->
            <div class="day-card" id="day17">
                <div class="day-header">
                    <span class="day-title">Day 17: Introduction to Provocative Testing</span>
                    <span class="day-date">Week 3, Day 3</span>
                </div>
                
                <div class="day-theme">
                    <h4>Today's Focus: Proving Your Brain Creates Symptoms from Imagination</h4>
                    <p>The most powerful evidence that pain is neuroplastic.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="education-section">
                    <h4>📚 The Magic of Provocative Testing</h4>
                    <p>If simply IMAGINING an activity creates symptoms, that's 100% proof your brain is generating them. Structural damage can't be triggered by imagination. This isn't "all in your head" - your brain creates real physical symptoms. But if imagination can create them, retraining can stop them.</p>
                    
                    <div class="key-concept">
                        <strong>The Proof:</strong> A patient imagined pressing on a tender spot and pain increased. When asked to imagine pressing with joy and safety, the pain disappeared. The tender spot hadn't changed - only the brain's interpretation changed.
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="exercises-section">
                    <h4>Today's Exercises</h4>
                    
                    <div class="exercise-item">
                        <div class="exercise-header">
                            <span class="exercise-title">Morning Provocative Testing Session</span>
                            <span class="exercise-time">15 min</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="exercise-content">
                            <div class="provocative-box">
                                <h5>Your First Provocative Test</h5>
                                
                                <p><strong>Choose your LEAST scary trigger to imagine (not your worst!):</strong></p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Sitting for 30 minutes</li>
                                    <li>Walking a block</li>
                                    <li>Having sex</li>
                                    <li>Bending over</li>
                                    <li>Exercise</li>
                                </ul>
                                
                                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Step 1: Baseline (1 min)</strong></p>
                                <p>Rate current pelvic sensation: ___/10</p>
                                
                                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Step 2: Imagine with Fear (2 min)</strong></p>
                                <p>Close eyes. Vividly imagine doing the trigger activity. Imagine it going badly, causing pain. Notice: Do symptoms increase? Where? How much?</p>
                                
                                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Step 3: The Key Realization (1 min)</strong></p>
                                <p>If symptoms increased: "My brain just created symptoms from imagination alone! This is neuroplastic!"</p>
                                
                                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Step 4: Calm the System (2 min)</strong></p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>"I'm safe, this is just my brain protecting me"</li>
                                    <li>"These sensations can't hurt me"</li>
                                    <li>Track symptoms with curiosity until they reduce</li>
                                </ul>
                                
                                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Step 5: Imagine with Joy (2 min)</strong></p>
                                <p>Now imagine the SAME activity but with confidence, ease, and joy. See yourself doing it perfectly comfortably. Notice: Symptoms different?</p>
                            </div>
                            
                            <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Journal Discovery:</strong> "Imagining [activity] with fear created ___. Imagining with joy created ___. This proves my brain controls these sensations."</p>
                            
                            <div class="checkbox-wrapper">
                                <input type="checkbox" id="day17-provocative">
                                <label for="day17-provocative">Completed provocative testing!</label>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="exercise-item">
                        <div class="exercise-header">
                            <span class="exercise-title">Endo Reality Integration</span>
                            <span class="exercise-time">10 min</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="exercise-content">
                            <p><strong>Write about this dual reality:</strong></p>
                            
                            <div style="background: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 15px 0;">
                                <p>"I have endometriosis that creates some legitimate inflammation and tissue irritation. AND my brain is amplifying these signals by 300-400% because it thinks I'm in danger."</p>
                                
                                <p style="margin-top: 10px;">"When I imagined [activity], my brain created symptoms instantly. The endo didn't suddenly get worse in those 2 minutes - my brain created the increase."</p>
                                
